      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9432b668e547492c",
      "text": "Again, I have to leave a lot out of it here: it is only a matter of proving that a certain, namely Christian, understanding of truth is essentially responsible for this downfall. And, so much in advance, to give an impression of what I actually want to get at here: The emergence of capitalism is unthinkable if one does not take into account a profound change in the concept of exactly this Christian truth."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "545c259aa1725949",
      "text": "We come to the official founder of this Christianity (only official: the real founder was undoubtedly the Roman Paul), that is, Jesus. He grew up in a society of Jews who, because of the Roman occupation, began to despair of their unity in God. Besides Jesus, many were firmly convinced that there was a need for a renewal of trust in their God from the bottom up. The vast majority, however, wanted nothing more than to follow in the footsteps of the old prophets and renew the binding nature of the old laws. This Jesus, however, fell for a very special idea: not only did he pretend to be one sent by God, but he boldly and freely claimed that he himself was the Son of God, and not only that: he himself was God."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bd434262018a2083",
      "text": "What was said above for the handing over of the ten commandments to the Jews by Moses, applies in relation to Jesus at first just as: What at first sight provokes nothing but head shaking not only with us, but even more with the contemporaries at that time, proves on the second as everything else than stupid. Because if one simply accepts it - against the first view - that Jesus is really God, then the problem of the mediation, the overcoming of the absolute separation of God and man, has elegantly settled. In Jesus the synthesis of God and world is represented. From here, if this construction is to present itself as reasonable, at least at second glance, the presumption, which this claim of this Jesus to be God and man at the same time undoubtedly represents, must now be relativized. And for this there is only one possibility: The concept of God must be conceived in such a way that it remains the unity which it is for the Jews, and which the Jesus-followers also did not want to question, but nevertheless also allows that this one God also becomes conceivable as a double. God, - I come back to the problem of truth -, conceived as the unity, the synthesis, in short: the truth of the separation of God the Father and God the Son, represents the solution to the problem of being able to present Jesus as God without falling behind everything that the Old Testament had revealed as an inalienable truth about the one God."
