        "id": "f923329bf18e6043",
        "text": "This is exactly what Christianity succeeds in doing in following Jesus. And exactly in the way as described above, namely that the monstrosity of the assertion, Jesus was God's son, sets a logic in motion, in which the meaningfulness of the second look takes away the first its absurdity. It was clear to the first disciples of Jesus that after his execution they had to prove that he was immortal: otherwise he would not be God after all. And so he appeared to them and to some others even after his death. Thus they followed a logic, of which even their master probably had not even a clue. And then Paul came. He recognized the social potential of this claim and adapted the teachings of this Jesus so congenially to the reality of the Roman Empire that modern Protestantism, too, in its effort to give capital the religion it deserves, only had to follow his lead. An awareness of which logic he followed in this adaptation was needed by Paul as little as by Protestantism, and as little as by the state religion of the Eastern Roman, i.e. Byzantine empire, and as little as by Islam: their endeavor was to become state religion, and thus to regenerate an obedience to the empire in question, which welded its members into a unity that made military coercion within it as superfluous as possible."
