      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "a16009bb2cd651c0",
        "text": "Of course – I refer to what I have explained about the separation of theory and practice – one cannot imagine the further unfolding of Christianity into a mass movement that brought the Roman Empire to its knees as if Jesus had armed his apostles with a correct theory that now conquered the masses at a run. Rather, Jesus' claim to be the Son of God meets a situation in which he promises to overcome a crisis in which people want to rediscover their general coherence, a unity and truth that allows them to come to terms with their fear; a fear that has been inherent in them since they left tribal societies, and which in the Old Testament is indissolubly linked to the concept of original sin: the fear of having to recognize that a unity other than the one their mortal body offers them does not in fact exist. With Jesus, conceived as the Son of God, they were able to place themselves in a unity that promised redemption to their torments of soul."
